<font color="#FF0000">WANNABES</font><br>
<tt>Sun Mar  9  1:03:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Someone &quot;wishing&quot; or &quot;envying&quot; to be someone he isn't, gets no sympathy from me.<br><br>
Vets who served in Vietnam ARE. Those who didn't AIN'T. That is where it ends.<br><br>
People fail to realize that lofty aspirations are achieved every day in peacetime. My oldest son will graduate from college this spring. My next oldest son is married with a small child. My last son 16 years old knows a hell of a lot about computers. At there respective ages they are much further along than I was - by far.<br><br>
I wish I could take credit for their successes - but the credit goes to them. If they go on to lead good, honest lives and sacrifice for the good of their families, they are NO LESS than anyone who served in Vietnam. <br><br>
The purpose of Veterans of Vietnam today should be in picking up the pieces of America's greatest tragedy. That can start here on the Internet by sharing information and by encouraging those less fortunate to hang in there.<br><br>
A PRETENDER is concerned about his image to the extent that he would steal from those who laid it on the line and have paid the consequences for the last 30 years. They are only one example of the dishonesty and insincerity that prevails in all segments of our society today.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


